Part 4

The press meet was held in the Bagbazar courtyard, under the shade of the largest neem tree. There were six plastic chairs arranged near the well, and one table covered with a faded green cloth. 

Three reporters from the local Bengali dailies had arrived, along with a photographer who spent ten minutes cleaning his camera lens with his shirt tail before taking a single shot of the courtyard well.

Sarita sat near the table. She had returned from Delhi the night before, her wooden walking stick now carrying a small brass cap at the bottom that made a soft ringing sound against the stone floor. 

Vikram stood near the green side gate. 

A woman was sitting on the second plastic chair, holding a small reporter's notepad. She had grey hair at the temples, her glasses thick and tied to a black cord around her neck. 

She was talking to a silver-haired man beside her, whose name was Aftab. He was her husband.

Vikram looked at her. The shape of the eyelids was the same, and the way she held the pen, the tip touching her lower lip as she read her notes, was identical. 

It was Ira. 

She looked up, her eyes moving across the courtyard. She saw him standing near the gate, his faded cotton shirt dusty from the sweeping work.

She stood up. She didn't run; she walked slowly, her sandals clicking against the stone tiles he had reset himself.

"Vikram," she said, her voice soft.

"Ira," Vikram said.

Aftab had followed her. He stood beside her, his face quiet and respectful, nodding to Vikram with the distance of a husband who had been told a version of an old story a long time ago.

"This is Aftab," she said. "We edit the Cuttack weekly newspaper now."

"I know," Vikram said.

"I saw the shelter," she said, looking around the clean courtyard and at Ananya who was writing in the green ledger. "It is good work, Vikram. The auto drivers at the crossing told me about the medicine deliveries. They call you Budha Baba."

"They have many names," Vikram said, his voice flat.

He looked at her eyes. "The cream-colored car," he said. "The one near the press building."

Ira looked down at her notepad, her hand adjusting her glasses. "I sold it," she said, her voice dropping. "Two weeks after you left it there. I used the money to clear my father's bank loan. It was enough to start the Cuttack weekly." 

She looked at him again. "Thank you, Vikram. For leaving it."

"Rohan's office," Vikram said. "The letters you sent."

Ira's brow furrowed, her eyes showing genuine confusion. "Letters? I never sent any letters, Vikram. I haven't spoken to Rohan or his office since 1997."

Vikram felt a small, cold drop of sweat slide down his neck.

"The yellow envelope," he said. "From Cuttack. Rehman."

Ira looked at Aftab. Aftab looked at Vikram, his eyes moving from Vikram's face to the leather bag resting near the well.

"Rehman?" Ira asked. "Who is Rehman?"

"Your son," Vikram said, his voice rising slightly. "The boy who came to work here."

Ira stared at him. It was not a look of anger, but the deep, slow confusion of a journalist who has just realized a source is speaking in a language she doesn't understand.

"Vikram," she said, her voice very quiet. "I never had a son."

She paused, looking at her husband. "Aftab and I... we were married in ninety-eight. We didn't have children."

---

The telephone cabin on the corner of the Bagbazar lane smelled of old directories and dry tobacco. Vikram stood inside, his hand trembling as he dialled the phone number Rehman had left. 

It was the number he had written in the ledger margins next to Rehman's name.

A click came from the exchange. Then the recorded voice, dry and mechanical, spoke:

*The number you have dialled does not exist. Please check the directory.*

He dialled again, his fingers cold. The same voice returned.

He hung up and walked back to the shelter courtyard. Ananya was sitting at her register table.

"Ananya," Vikram said. "Rehman's canvas bag. The blue one. Where is it?"

"He took it, uncle," she said. "When he went to Alipore."

"The photo," Vikram said. "The one he showed you on his phone. The one of his mother."

Ananya looked at him, her pen stopping over the green ledger. "He never showed me a photo, uncle."

"He did," Vikram said, his voice sharp. "In the kitchen. The day he arrived."

"No, uncle," she said, her eyes large and quiet. "He only had the wooden horse. He said he found it near the well. He never showed me a phone. He didn't have a phone."

Vikram walked into the study. The yellow envelope was sitting on the teak wood desk, near the brass lion paperweight. 

He picked it up and pulled out the two ruled sheets of paper.

The paper was completely empty. No Cuttack press details, no handwriting, and no story of conversion. 

It was a property tax receipt from the municipal corporation, dated March 2015, sent to the *Ahuja Villa* address and forwarded by the local clerk.

---

The lawyer, Bannerjee, arrived at six in the evening. He sat on the step of the well, his leather briefcase kept on his knees. He didn't open it.

"The CEO transfer deed," Vikram said. "Where is it?"

"In my office, Vikram babu," the lawyer said.

"Whose name is on the recipient line?"

Bannerjee looked at the drumstick tree. "Your name," he said.

"My name?"

"Yes. The power of attorney was drafted in your name. You signed it, but you left the second signature blank. You told me Rehman would sign in Alipore."

"He did sign," Vikram said. "He called me. He said he saw the blue blur."

"Nobody signed, Vikram babu," the lawyer said, his voice dropping in the quiet courtyard. "The papers are still in my briefcase. I went to Alipore. The apartment was registered in the name of *Ummed Trust*, which is a subsidiary of Punarjeevan. The keys were with the security guard."

He looked at Vikram properly now. "The guard said you rented the flat three years ago. You paid the rent in advance from the Odisha bank account. Nobody ever lived there, Vikram babu."

"The silver sedan?"

"The sedan was bought by the trust," Bannerjee said. "You bought it yourself in 2018. It has been sitting in the Alipore garage since the day of purchase."

Vikram sat on the stone wall of the well. The red tea was boiling in the kitchen, the smell of ginger coming through the window. But the glass on the ledge was empty.

He looked at his hands, at the calluses, at the grey dirt under the nails. 

The fourteen hundred crore was in Nandyal. The seventy-six hundred crore was in Alipore. 

But the boy with the blue canvas bag and the rusted zip was nowhere in the city. He had never been.

